The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Shah Rukh co-host for the IPL awards
                                                                                                                       7                                      Shah Rukh co-host for the IPL awards
            OUR CORRESPONDENT                      
	Mumbai: Kolkata Knight Riders principal owner Shah Rukh Khan and Bollywood buddy Karan Johar will be the hosts at the gala function for the inaugural IPL Awards to be held here on April 23.         
	The awards would reward performances in the league stage of the tournament with 22 trophies to be given away under three categories: Jury awards, Viewers Choice awards and Statistical awards.         
	Besides, there is also the Captains award, wherein the captains of the franchises will pick the Indian legend they would want to play for their team.         
	The IPL awards jury comprises former players Sunil Gavaskar, Brian Lara and Javagal Srinath, umpire Simon Taufel and commentator Harsha Bhogle while IPL chairman Lalit Modi will be the convenor.         
	Some of Indian cinemas biggest names, including AR Rahman, Shilpa Shetty, Katrina Kaif, Priyanka Chopra and Hrithik Roshan, are set to bring their trademark energy and style to the ceremony, Modi said at a function.         
	Awards under the Jury category are: Best Ground, Best IPL Debutant, Best Stadium Experience, Most Consistent Performer, Most Dramatic Performance, Best Fielder, Best Bowler, Best Batsman and Breakthrough Performance by a batsman or bowler.         
	The Viewers Choice awards includes: Best Commentator, Most Fan Friendly Cricketer, Best Catch, Most Stylish Player, Best Fielder, Best Captain, Best Bowler and Best Batsman.         
	Under the Statistical category, awards would be presented for maximum runs scored from boundaries, the fastest 100 and the most economical bowler.         
	It was also learnt that the fourth season of the IPL, featuring 10 teams, will commence in the first week of April next year, soon after the conclusion of the ICC ODI World Cup, IPL commissioner Lalit Modi said on Wednesday.         
	We are going to start the 2011 IPL season a few days after the World Cup in the first week of April.         
	We are going back to the schedule of April-May that we had in the 2008 first season. We will keep this (schedule) in future, Modi said.         
	Two more teams have been added to the existing outfits Pune and Kochi  and there will be a total of 94 matches, an increase of 34 ties from the ongoing edition.                                                                                                                     
